if we test just the diff-filtering function in isolation. But the behavior is \"review input IS scoped\", which means we need to test end-to-end that the input to the analysis is scoped. That's Integration - multiple modules (diff parser, analysis) working together.\n\n\nThe phrasing \"the review input IS scoped\" suggests verifying the full automation pipeline only analyzes changed lines, not just testing the diff-filtering function alone. This requires the diff parser and analysis module to work together, making it Integration. System-level testing would only apply if the diff source itself (like a GitHub API call) were part of the failure boundary, but mocking that dependency keeps this at Integration.\n\nThe actual failure mode is when a real PR diff with changes across multiple locations gets passed to analysis—the test needs to confirm the handoff between diff parsing and analysis is correct, ensuring only the changed lines reach the analyzer. This is fundamentally about module integration rather than isolated unit behavior.\n\nThe confidence breakdown reflects this: integration testing is most appropriate here (0.75) since the real risk lies in the pipeline handoff, while unit testing alone (0.1) wouldn't catch integration failures, and system-level testing (0.1) only matters if GitHub API fetching is the actual problem.\n\nFor the second behavior around inline comments, the concern is whether comments post at the correct line numbers when the diff parser and comment posting module interact. The failure would manifest as a mismatch—the parser identifies line 42 as changed but the comment gets posted at line 39 instead.\n\nTesting this requires deciding what \"correct positions in the diff view\" actually means: either verifying the right data structure reaches GitHub's API (integration test with mocks), or confirming the comment visibly appears at the right spot on a real PR (system test). The distinction matters because mocking the GitHub API lets us validate the handoff between modules without external dependencies, but it doesn't guarantee GitHub will interpret our line numbers correctly.\n\nI'm leaning toward integration testing since the core failure is likely in how we format the line number for GitHub's API rather than GitHub's own behavior. We'd mock the API call and verify it receives the correct payload. However, there's meaningful risk that the real issue only surfaces with actual GitHub—their diff context handling might differ from our assumptions, making this partially a system-level concern.\n\nFor Behavior 3, the core question is whether an LLM will actually detect a specific defect in real code. This fundamentally depends on the model's capabilities and behavior, making it agentic. The non-determinism matters here—running the same PR through the model multiple times could yield different results. However, I should consider whether we could test this with a deterministic approach or if the \"at least one real defect\" phrasing changes the classification.\n\nThe behavior explicitly requires the agent to identify defects, not just post comments. We can't mock away the LLM judgment without losing what we're actually testing. This is clearly agentic work.\n\nFor Behavior 4, the focus shifts to consistency between the summary and inline comments. This is about the agent's ability to maintain coherence across its outputs—ensuring every finding gets properly documented both places. This could potentially be tested at lower levels by mocking the LLM's findings and verifying the posting logic, but the real behavior depends on how the agent actually generates and tracks findings. The test would verify that every finding appearing in the summary also has a corresponding inline comment posted—this requires mocking both the findings list and the posting modules, making it fundamentally an integration concern rather than a unit test of the summary module alone.\n\nIntegration testing is most appropriate here since we're validating coordination between the analysis module, inline-posting module, and summary-posting module. The confidence assessment reflects this: 0.75 for integration (verifying module coordination), 0.15 for unit (could isolate summary filtering logic), and minimal weight for system, agentic, or workflow categories.\n\nFor the end-to-end workflow scenario, the full sequence—reading the diff, posting inline comments, posting the summary—executing correctly against a real pull request without manual intervention represents a system-level concern, particularly if failures stem from GitHub API interactions or other external dependencies. \"Real pull request\" likely means a realistic scenario rather than an actual GitHub interaction. The test needs real LLM analysis to evaluate whether the agent correctly identifies issues in the code diff, then orchestrates posting comments and summaries. Since there's only one agentic step (the analysis itself), this isn't about multiple steps. The core question is whether the agent properly analyzes the PR and completes the full sequence—which points to **Agentic** if the focus is on analysis quality, or **System** if it requires actual GitHub API calls. Given the emphasis on \"real pull request\" and realistic code analysis, this seems to be testing whether the LLM can genuinely understand and respond to actual code changes. (could mock externals, but the behavior truly depends on real interactions). The confidence breakdown reflects this: System at 0.6 since it requires both real GitHub and LLM working together, Agentic at 0.2 since LLM quality matters but isn't the primary concern, and Workflow at 0.1 since there's only one agentic step rather than multiple sequential ones. Reconsidering the definitions, the core issue isn't model judgment quality—it's whether the entire sequence executes correctly end-to-end with real external systems.\n\nThe failure modes clarify this: GitHub API returning malformed data, the parser crashing, LLM analysis finding nothing, API rejecting comment formats, or the sequence breaking due to exception handling. These span multiple layers, but the real boundary is System integration—whether GitHub and the LLM work together properly to complete the full workflow.\n\nI could argue this is Workflow since it's a complete agent pipeline with reasoning and output generation. However, System feels more precise because the primary constraint is real external dependencies (GitHub API and LLM), not just the orchestration of steps. The behavior fundamentally depends on these systems functioning together, which makes System the right classification.\n\nThe key question is whether mocking GitHub would still satisfy the \"real pull request\" requirement. If we can use realistic mock data, Integration testing might suffice. But the explicit mention of \"real pull request\" suggests actual GitHub interaction is necessary, which pushes this toward System testing. Real failures here would include API rejections or authentication issues that only surface with genuine external calls. not complete in sequence) → Workflow?\n\nThe core issue seems to be module coordination and completeness, though real GitHub interaction is involved. Reading the diff and posting comments could work with mocks at the Integration level, but the requirement for \"real pull request\" suggests System-level testing is necessary.\n\nConsidering what's needed to catch each failure: diff parsing requires either Integration with mocks or System with real GitHub; analysis needs the actual LLM; comment posting works with mocks or real API; sequence completion can be verified through mocked orchestration. The limiting factor is real GitHub interaction, pointing to System as the appropriate level.\n\nThough I could test the full workflow with a realistic mock GitHub client and verify all steps execute in order, the explicit mention of \"a real pull request\" and potential API formatting failures that a lenient mock might miss suggest System-level testing is the safest approach.\n\nThe core question is whether failures are orchestration-based (sequence breaks) or transport-based (GitHub API rejects malformed requests). Since the behavior emphasizes real interactions and API format issues could slip through Integration testing, I'm settling on **System** as my final answer, though Integration remains a reasonable alternative.\n\nMy confidence distribution reflects this: System at 0.7 because real GitHub and LLM interactions are necessary to catch actual API failures, Integration at 0.2 for mocked alternatives, and Agentic/Workflow each at 0.05 since the focus isn't on LLM reasoning quality or full agent orchestration but rather on whether the sequence executes without transport errors.\n\nLooking back at all five behaviors, I'm seeing a pattern. The first behavior needs integration testing for diff filtering, the second requires verifying module positioning logic, the third is clearly agentic since it hinges on LLM judgment quality, the fourth depends on module coordination, and the fifth demands real external interactions. For behavior two specifically, I should reconsider—the GitHub diff view placement could fail at the API level if the request is malformed, or at the module level if positioning logic is wrong.\n\nTo truly verify comments land in the correct diff positions, I'd need either actual GitHub interaction or a mock that somehow validates the display behavior. But mocking GitHub doesn't actually confirm the diff view renders correctly. That pushes it toward system testing.\n\nRevising my assessment: behavior one stays integration, behavior two shifts to system since real GitHub verification is needed, behavior three remains agentic, behavior four stays integration, and behavior five stays system.\n\nActually, reconsidering—an integration test could catch most failures by mocking both GitHub and the diff parser to verify the right line number gets sent. That would catch off-by-one errors and format issues. GitHub's diff view rendering itself would only be caught at the system level. So integration is the minimum viable level for this specific behavior, though system testing would be more complete.\n\nFor #5, \"completes correctly for a real pull request\" seems to emphasize whether the sequence runs end-to-end, which points to system testing. Though there's also the question of whether the findings themselves are correct, which depends on the LLM's analytical capability. I'm leaning toward system as the answer.\n\nOn #5 though, I should think more carefully about what \"Workflow\" actually means—it's supposed to be multiple agentic steps or a full agent pipeline. Looking at this automation: it reads input (not agentic), runs one LLM analysis (agentic), then posts output (not agentic). That's only a single agentic step, so it doesn't really fit the \"full pipeline\" definition.\n\nA true agent pipeline would involve sequential decision-making—analyze the diff, decide where to comment based on that analysis, potentially iterate on feedback, then finalize. This has just the one analysis step, so **System** is the right classification for #5, not Workflow.\n\nFor my final answers: #1 is **Integration** (0.75 confidence), #2 is **Integration** (0.65 confidence, though System at 0.25 is also reasonable), and #3 is **Agentic**.\n\nNow I need to verify each classification against the \"plan_consistent\" criterion—would the test actually require that level, or would it pass at something lower? For #1, the scoped input test could theoretically be a Unit test of just the diff filtering function, but the behavior requires validating it within the full pipeline context, making Integration necessary.\n\nFor #2, correct positions could be Unit-tested in isolation, yet verifying accurate line numbers in the actual diff view demands Integration-level testing with mocked GitHub interactions. System testing would catch GitHub-specific display issue